---
import DocsLayout from "../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
import CodeBlock from "../../components/CodeBlock.astro";
import Callout from "../../components/Callout.astro";

const getMerchantSnippet = `const [error, response] = await wompi.merchants.getMerchant();
if (error) throw error;

const merchant = response;

merchant.name;          // string | undefined
merchant.legal_name;    // string | undefined
merchant.accepted_payment_methods;  // string[] | undefined
merchant.presigned_acceptance?.acceptance_token; // string`;

const acceptanceSnippet = `const [error, response] = await wompi.merchants.getMerchant();
if (error) throw error;

const acceptance = response.presigned_acceptance;

// Persist for the duration of a single transaction — Wompi rotates these.
return {
  token: acceptance?.acceptance_token,
  termsUrl: acceptance?.permalink,
};`;
---

<DocsLayout
  section="API Reference"
  title="Merchants"
  description="Fetch merchant info and the presigned acceptance token required for every transaction."
>
  <p>
    The merchant endpoint is the only one that needs no authentication header — the public key
    travels as part of the URL. Use it to fetch merchant metadata and, crucially, the presigned
    acceptance token you must include in every <code>createTransaction</code> call.
  </p>

  <h2 id="getmerchant">getMerchant()</h2>
  <p>
    <code>GET /merchants/&#123;publicKey&#125;</code>. Returns the merchant record. Requires only the public
    key (passed at client construction).
  </p>

  <CodeBlock code={getMerchantSnippet} lang="ts" />

  <h2 id="response-shape">Response shape</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Field</th>
        <th>Type</th>
        <th>Notes</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>id</code></td><td><code>number</code></td><td>Wompi merchant id.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>name</code></td><td><code>string?</code></td><td>Public merchant name.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>legal_name</code></td><td><code>string?</code></td><td>Legal entity name.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>legal_id</code> / <code>legal_id_type</code></td><td><code>string?</code></td><td><code>NIT</code> or <code>CC</code>.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>accepted_payment_methods</code></td><td><code>string[]?</code></td><td><code>"CARD"</code>, <code>"NEQUI"</code>, <code>"PSE"</code>, …</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>accepted_currencies</code></td><td><code>"COP"[]?</code></td><td>Always <code>["COP"]</code> today.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>presigned_acceptance</code></td><td><code>object?</code></td><td>See below.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2 id="presigned-acceptance">Presigned acceptance</h2>
  <p>
    The <code>presigned_acceptance</code> object proves the customer accepted the merchant's
    end-user policy. Show <code>permalink</code> to the customer; pass
    <code>acceptance_token</code> when you create a transaction.
  </p>

  <CodeBlock code={acceptanceSnippet} lang="ts" />

  <ul>
    <li><code>acceptance_token</code> — string, expires; fetch once per transaction.</li>
    <li><code>permalink</code> — URL to the merchant's terms.</li>
    <li><code>type</code> — always <code>"END_USER_POLICY"</code>.</li>
  </ul>

  <Callout type="tip" title="Cache, but only briefly">
    The acceptance token is short-lived. Refetch it for every transaction rather than caching it
    across requests — the request is fast and cheap, and a stale token is a guaranteed
    <code>INPUT_VALIDATION_ERROR</code>.
  </Callout>

  <h2 id="errors">Errors</h2>
  <p>
    The endpoint is public, so authentication errors don't apply. Possible
    <code>error</code> values:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><code>WompiNotFoundError</code> — public key doesn't match any merchant.</li>
    <li><code>WompiRequestError</code> — any other non-2xx response.</li>
  </ul>
</DocsLayout>
